{"type":"user.message","data":{"content":"I'm migrating a .NET 9 app to .NET 10. Here's code that worked before:\n\n```csharp\n[JsonPolymorphic(TypeDiscriminatorPropertyName = \"Type\")]\n[JsonDerivedType(typeof(Dog), \"dog\")]\npublic abstract class Animal\n{\n    public abstract string Type { get; }\n}\n\npublic class Dog : Animal\n{\n    public override string Type => \"Dog\";\n}\n\n// This produced {\"Type\":\"dog\",\"Type\":\"Dog\"} in .NET 9 — broken JSON but it serialized\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize<Animal>(new Dog());\n```\n\n```csharp\npublic class OrderDto\n{\n    public int Id { get; set; }\n    [Obsolete(\"Use ShippingAddress instead\")]\n    public string Address { get; set; }\n    public string ShippingAddress { get; set; }\n}\nvar xml = new XmlSerializer(typeof(OrderDto));\n// In .NET 9, Address was not included in the serialized output\n```\n\nThe app also validates email addresses like `user..name@example.com` with MailAddress, and uses Uri for 10K+ character URLs.\nWhat breaks?\n","transformedContent":"<current_datetime>2026-05-12T01:06:59.025Z</current_datetime>\n\nI'm migrating a .NET 9 app to .NET 10. Here's code that worked before:\n\n```csharp\n[JsonPolymorphic(TypeDiscriminatorPropertyName = \"Type\")]\n[JsonDerivedType(typeof(Dog), \"dog\")]\npublic abstract class Animal\n{\n    public abstract string Type { get; }\n}\n\npublic class Dog : Animal\n{\n    public override string Type => \"Dog\";\n}\n\n// This produced {\"Type\":\"dog\",\"Type\":\"Dog\"} in .NET 9 — broken JSON but it serialized\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize<Animal>(new Dog());\n```\n\n```csharp\npublic class OrderDto\n{\n    public int Id { get; set; }\n    [Obsolete(\"Use ShippingAddress instead\")]\n    public string Address { get; set; }\n    public string ShippingAddress { get; set; }\n}\nvar xml = new XmlSerializer(typeof(OrderDto));\n// In .NET 9, Address was not included in the serialized output\n```\n\nThe app also validates email addresses like `user..name@example.com` with MailAddress, and uses Uri for 10K+ character URLs.\nWhat breaks?","attachments":[],"interactionId":"4559c8d9-5750-456d-b4c6-95b2d82b3797"},"id":"034895e8-90c3-44d5-a2f7-9286d69e938d","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:06:59.025Z","parentId":"95dc4ac0-e5e2-4204-bc14-8acdc54d0f0e"}
{"type":"hook.start","data":{"hookInvocationId":"f79fdcd3-6913-4271-be5e-df8cc059b531","hookType":"sessionStart","input":{"sessionId":"5951e3a0-76e6-4505-b43a-6f7ba3901d64","timestamp":1778548019026,"cwd":"/tmp/sv-0967c97b335d41e198fa1f5bf9c9dac2","source":"new","initialPrompt":"I'm migrating a .NET 9 app to .NET 10. Here's code that worked before:\n\n```csharp\n[JsonPolymorphic(TypeDiscriminatorPropertyName = \"Type\")]\n[JsonDerivedType(typeof(Dog), \"dog\")]\npublic abstract class Animal\n{\n    public abstract string Type { get; }\n}\n\npublic class Dog : Animal\n{\n    public override string Type => \"Dog\";\n}\n\n// This produced {\"Type\":\"dog\",\"Type\":\"Dog\"} in .NET 9 — broken JSON but it serialized\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize<Animal>(new Dog());\n```\n\n```csharp\npublic class OrderDto\n{\n    public int Id { get; set; }\n    [Obsolete(\"Use ShippingAddress instead\")]\n    public string Address { get; set; }\n    public string ShippingAddress { get; set; }\n}\nvar xml = new XmlSerializer(typeof(OrderDto));\n// In .NET 9, Address was not included in the serialized output\n```\n\nThe app also validates email addresses like `user..name@example.com` with MailAddress, and uses Uri for 10K+ character URLs.\nWhat breaks?\n"}},"id":"f4213ec3-f8a1-441a-ab7b-a32abc5b9e5c","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:06:59.026Z","parentId":"034895e8-90c3-44d5-a2f7-9286d69e938d"}
